<subSubSection id="C36365068116F116FF212357FDD6FAE2" pageId="15" pageNumber="48" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BC6368D8116F116FF212357FEF5FBEB" blockId="15.[189,310,1033,1059]" box="[189,310,1033,1059]" pageId="15" pageNumber="48">
<heading id="D08E81E18116F116FF212357FEF5FBEB" bold="true" box="[189,310,1033,1059]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="15" pageNumber="48" reason="3">
<emphasis id="B90DEA9F8116F116FF212357FEF5FBEB" bold="true" box="[189,310,1033,1059]" pageId="15" pageNumber="48">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC6368D8116F116FF212366FDD6FAE2" blockId="15.[189,1399,1080,1323]" pageId="15" pageNumber="48">
Body dark-brown, antennae, mouthparts and legs red-brown. 
<taxonomicName id="4C794D0E8116F116FC432366FB2DFB9A" authorityName="Polizei &amp; Costa &amp; Bispo" authorityYear="2022" box="[991,1262,1080,1106]" class="Insecta" family="Elmidae" genus="Spanglerelmis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="timburi">
<emphasis id="B90DEA9F8116F116FC432366FB2DFB9A" box="[991,1262,1080,1106]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="48">Spanglerelmis timburi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
resembles 
<taxonomicName id="4C794D0E8116F116FF212303FE8EFBBE" authorityName="Polizei &amp; Costa &amp; Bispo" authorityYear="2022" baseAuthorityName="Polizei &amp; Costa &amp; Bispo" baseAuthorityYear="1940" box="[189,333,1116,1143]" class="Insecta" family="Elmidae" genus="Microcylloepus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="femoralis">
<emphasis id="B90DEA9F8116F116FF212303FE8EFBBE" box="[189,333,1116,1143]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="48">S. femoralis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the profemora swollen but can be differentiated by the elytral interval IV with first puncture bigger and deeper than any others; metatibia without spur; and male genitalia with phallobase 1.5× as long as the penis, approximately 2.5× as long as wide; and penis 4× as long as wide. While in 
<taxonomicName id="4C794D0E8116F116FF222397FE8AFB2B" authorityName="Polizei &amp; Costa &amp; Bispo" authorityYear="2022" baseAuthorityName="Polizei &amp; Costa &amp; Bispo" baseAuthorityYear="1940" box="[190,329,1225,1251]" class="Insecta" family="Elmidae" genus="Microcylloepus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="femoralis">
<emphasis id="B90DEA9F8116F116FF222397FE8AFB2B" box="[190,329,1225,1251]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="48">S. femoralis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the first elytral puncture on interval IV is not bigger and deeper than any others; metatibia with a spur; male genitalia with phallobase 2× as long as the penis, approximately 4× as long as wide; and penis 3× as long as wide.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C36365068116F116FF21220DFC61FA2D" pageId="15" pageNumber="48" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BC6368D8116F116FF21220DFE87FAA5" blockId="15.[189,324,1363,1389]" box="[189,324,1363,1389]" pageId="15" pageNumber="48">
<heading id="D08E81E18116F116FF21220DFE87FAA5" bold="true" box="[189,324,1363,1389]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="15" pageNumber="48" reason="3">
<emphasis id="B90DEA9F8116F116FF21220DFE87FAA5" bold="true" box="[189,324,1363,1389]" pageId="15" pageNumber="48">Etymology</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC6368D8116F116FF2122DCFC61FA2D" blockId="15.[188,1399,1410,1510]" pageId="15" pageNumber="48">
The specific epithet 
<taxonomicName id="4C794D0E8116F116FE3222DCFDC6FA54" authorityName="Polizei &amp; Costa &amp; Bispo" authorityYear="2022" box="[430,517,1410,1436]" class="Insecta" family="Elmidae" genus="Spanglerelmis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="timburi">
<emphasis id="B90DEA9F8116F116FE3222DCFDC6FA54" box="[430,517,1410,1436]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="48">timburi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
refers to the Timburi county (
<collectingRegion id="49BDF86F8116F116FCF122DDFBEFFA55" box="[877,1068,1410,1437]" country="Brazil" name="Sao Paulo" pageId="15" pageNumber="48">São Paulo State</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry id="F36E761D8116F116FBA522DCFB41FA55" box="[1081,1154,1410,1437]" name="Brazil" pageId="15" pageNumber="48">Brazil</collectingCountry>
) where the 
<typeStatus id="54C2882F8116F116FA8C22DCFAB4FA54" box="[1296,1399,1410,1436]" pageId="15" pageNumber="48">holotype</typeStatus>
was collected. Timburi is the name of a very common tree (
<taxonomicName id="4C794D0E8116F116FCF222F9FB0DFA09" authority="Mart." authorityName="Mart." box="[878,1230,1447,1473]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Enterolobium" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="15" pageNumber="48" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="timbouva">
<emphasis id="B90DEA9F8116F116FCF222F9FB46FA09" box="[878,1157,1447,1473]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="48">Enterolobium timbouva</emphasis>
Mart.
</taxonomicName>
) in the region. It is an indigenous word (Tupi origin) meaning ‘nose or snout’.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
